segments.text: One of the interesting things, I don't know, do you remember what George Bush Drive looked like before we made the street out of it?
We got ready to build that and Mr. Greer, who was a state highway engineer, gave me $500,000 to build that street and didn't charge it to my
Farm to Market Road program because he had a love for A&M and he's a graduate of 1926 or somewhere back there.
So I went to Mr. Rutter and I told him that I had money to rebuild Jersey Street from Highway 6 over to the railroad.
That's as far as the first part of it went.
This was to take it from two lanes to four lanes.
Well, two lanes from nothing to something.
And that's part of my story.
Mr. Rutter called me and asked me, said, what's going to be your design on, called it Jersey Street at that time.
And I said, Mr. Rutter, we're going to build four running lanes, two parking lanes, and a continuous 16-foot left turn center lane.
You can't do that.
I come, you're going to take too much of my campus.
He said, build it like the road over there by the railroad.
And I said, no, sir, we're not going to build nothing like that.
Well, you think about it some more.
I said, that's going to take an awful lot of the campus.
So he called me in about two, three weeks, and he said, what did you decide about Jersey Street?
And I said, four running lanes, two parking lanes, and a 16-foot turn lane.
He said, I told you, you got to cut that down.
I said, Mr. Rutter, we're not going to spend any money out there if we can't build it right.
So the thing rocked along, and he called me about three or four weeks later, and he said, have you been talking to any of my board members?
I said, Mr. Rudd, I don't even know any board members.
He said, well, the last board meeting they told me, they said, when they get ready to build Jersey Street, don't let them build it too narrow.
I said, I don't know who he was, but he's my friend.
So...
you see what we built, and it's not wide enough.
But at that point, then, did he did agree?
Oh, yes.
Oh, another thing, he said, they're going to take his soccer field.
You know, the soccer field is where, I guess, the former student building is now.
I said, you can build a soccer field anywhere on this campus.
And then we got ready to go from the railroad over to the airport.
See, there wasn't any road there at all.
That was a pasture.
And we got the thing laid out, and we were working with a fellow, but it seemed to me like his name was Langdon or Langston or something, who was head of the utilities department out there.
And there was power lines and fence lines and water lines.
So we began to tell him that he had to move a bunch of that stuff and he was dragging his feet and he wouldn't, he just wasn't moving.
So I called Mr. Rutter and I said, Mr. Rutter, we can't get any clearance out there.
I said, we got power lines, water lines, and a bunch of stuff to move.
And I said, they're just dragging their feet.
And I said, you wanted that thing done.
He said, well, come out and tell me what you need.
And so I took my resin engineer and went out there.
And he said, just give me a list of what you want.
When you want the power line moved.
And I said, oh, three weeks or whatever we told him.
And water line, sort of the same.
And he said, OK, what else?
And I said, that's it.
He said, well, I'm going to Europe.
O.D.
Butler called me the next week.
And he said, what in the hell did you tell Mr. Rutter?
And I said, well, I just told him we had to get that stuff moved.
He said, he called me and he said, you get out there and you get that stuff moved right now.
O.D.
Butler was moving the fence the next week.
And Haskell, it wasn't any time till he got that thing, he got that thing clear.
He could move things.
And then we got ready to build the West Loop.
And he called me and Fort Albritton and, oh, I don't know, there was some of the county people.
They had built one little end on the north end of it from Highway 21 up.
The county had built a little short stretch.
And he told me, he said, we want 300 feet around there, so if you ever make it four lane, we don't have to get additional right of way.
And the university is going to give the county
whatever right of way they need, and pointed to Mr. Allbritton, and he said, Ford, and you're going to give what the need down.
He owned a bunch of it out there, about this intersection.
You know where Allbritton, the Linn Co. used to be?
Yeah, yeah.
That was Ford Allbritton.
Sure, sure.
And he owned then on out where the...
And Ford said later, I didn't know you were gonna put an interchange out there and we've got the world the right way.
But he told Ford, you're gonna give that.
And so he, man, he could move stuff, I'm not kidding you.
Of all the presidents you have observed, to which one at A&M, I'm not gonna ask the negative, to which ones would you give high grades?
Which presidents did the best job?
Well, as far as I was concerned, I guess it'd be Rudder and Williams.
That's the two that I dealt with a whole lot.
Give some examples of your work with Dr. Williams.
Well, the first real encounter I had with him, I don't know why, but I was out to a football game or something, or we'd had something before the football game, and I had my uniform on.
And we were walking along and met a man and woman and two little kids.
And I spoke to those little kids and the little boy was excited that he got to be a general officer.
And they told Mr. Williams about it for some reason.
I think they knew him or I can't tell you.
And he called me up and complimented me for stopping and putting my hand on that little boy.
And then we had two or three, there was two or three other road deals that he was involved with that I decided that he was a pretty nice fellow to work with.
Now during your day, was there discussion about moving the railroad?
No.
See, when I was in there, it used to be two railroads.
And we put them on one.
And that took 20 years.
To go over to the west side of the campus, you had to go up and climb up over the railroad like this and you couldn't see what was on the other side because there wasn't much over there.
And that was one of the oldest, we called it an IPE as a study job that the highway department had was to get rid of that bad crossing.
And there was an A&M graduate who was the chief engineer for the Southern Pacific Railroad in Houston.
And he's really the one that got that thing moved and we were able to put both of them, the highway department paid for putting those railroads together and building that underpass.
And he was responsible for that.
And so we worked a long time to get them on one railroad.
And I don't think I'm ever going to see any part of that railroad moved.
I agree with you very much.
I know I'm not going to.
You may, but I'm not going to live that long, I don't think.
And I really, Askel, I really don't think it's as big a problem as a lot of people think it is.
I agree, I agree.
Well, let's see.
We added this after the Aggie, what feelings you carry in your heart for A&M.
What do you hope, let's conclude with this, what do you hope A&M's future is?
What do you want A&M to be in the future?
Oh, I don't know that bigger is better.
I just hope that A&M can continue to carry the tradition it's got, have the leadership that is interested in it progressing and keeping the great name that it's got now.
That's a good conclusion.
